Tests are extremely useful to developers, but as projects get larger, tests can begin to get in the way of a smooth delivery pipeline. In this talk I present some issues I have experienced, and offer 10 pragmatic guidelines that may help developers maximize their test usefulness.</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">Ash Christopher</dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 11 Aug 2013 00:00:00 -0500</pubDate><guid>http://www.pyvideo.org/video/2333/testing-django-projects-at-scale</guid><enclosure url="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=91-LiEb3sPE" length="None" type="video/flv"></enclosure><media:thumbnail url="http://i1.ytimg.com/vi/91-LiEb3sPE/hqdefault.jpg"></media:thumbnail></item><item><title>Horizontally Scaling Your Database with Django</title><link>http://www.pyvideo.org/video/1576/horizontally-scaling-your-database-with-django</link><description>&lt;p&gt;Abstract&lt;/p&gt;
When web apps reach a certain size, often their data footprint will outgrow
what can reasonably be stored on a single database. Scaling your database
horizontally by adding more servers is the dream but it can be a daunting
task. This talk outlines the process I used to add horizontal scaling to Wave
Accounting's infrastructure.

